SIMPLE: obit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obit
<hw>O"bit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>obit</ets>, L.
<ets>obitus</ets>, fr. <ets>obire</ets> to go against, to go to meet,
(sc. <ets>mortem</ets>) to die; <ets>ob</ets> (see Ob-) + <ets>ire</ets>
to go. See <er>Issue</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Death; decease; the
date of one's death.</def> <rj><au>Wood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A funeral solemnity or office; obsequies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A service for the soul of a deceased person on the
anniversary of the day of his death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The emoluments and advantages from oblations, <qex>obits</qex>,
and other sources, increased in value.</q>
<rj><qau>Milman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Same as <er>obituary</er>; -- by
shortening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Post obit</b></col> <ety>[L. <ets>post
obitum</ets>]</ety>. <cd>See <er>Post-obit</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obiter</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
